e\n        public boolean isModifiableModule(Module module) {\n            return true;\n        }\n    }\n\n    private static final class ChildFirstClassLoader extends URLClassLoader {\n        private ChildFirstClassLoader(URL[] urls, ClassLoader parent) {\n            super(urls, parent);\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        protected Class<?> loadClass(String name, boolean resolve)\n                throws ClassNotFoundException {\n            synchronized (getClassLoadingLock(name)) {\n                Class<?> loadedClass = findLoadedClass(name);\n                if (loadedClass == null && isChildFirstClass(name)) {\n                    try {\n                        loadedClass = findClass(name);\n                    } catch (ClassNotFoundException ignored) {\n                        loadedClass = super.loadClass(name, false);\n                    }\n                } else if (loadedClass == null) {\n                    loadedClass = super.loadClass(name, false);\n                }\n                if (resolve) {\n                    resolveClass(loadedClass);\n                }\n                return loadedClass;\n            }\n        }\n\n        private static boolean isChildFirstClass(String name) {\n            return name.startsWith(\"org.modelmapper.\")\n                    || name.startsWith(FactoryScenario.class.getName())\n                    || name.startsWith(NoOpAccessResolver.class.getName())\n                    || name.startsWith(NoOpInstrumentation.class.getName());\n        }\n    }\n}\n"}
[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering test class structure**\n\nI need to ensure that my test doesn't attempt to load all child classes—just the nested scenario. It seems important to focus on the parent class, especially for AssertJ usage. I wonder what the best approach is to achieve this without overcomplicating the loading process. Is it possible to streamline it for efficiency? I want to make sure I’m doing this correctly, so I’ll keep researching to find the best solution!\n\n**Evaluating covariant returns**\n\nI’m thinking about whether covariant return types with Class<?>[] are allowed — it seems like they are. I’m also considering if existing checkstyle guidelines require no array brackets. I’ll need to import java.lang.instrument.* instead of using a wildcard for the style. Adding java.util.List might be necessary too. Oh, I should get started on writing that code!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_043b3b67990c61580169fc4218e7dc81a1946a4ee12d512854\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_EImOnXlDznjJfCUzMEC7Mq_yWoELD-n3zHpA405ggy2ou6lKvzLZj8KQ4L6TOW2GWrCED9zrf1w6FWZHgwgVWRzQUkK2PW6aSrKJWL3LeORat4HYePb4WKSFRVtUb_-gHLZH6Om0FHybVAgjKZzBDjtuO4l9NlHtKdXKnRoS_zMfV6WKSFLFTl9oWNBr2PQpICJt_O-9-k8QgG4srLtJ73L4RTZJD7sM6zUmvZhdWthCHYTBIlrzLKX1sJIqs3Iv-Rcvri5Q0J4aAwGAUfLkWoJKr9_D4km2k4wZ4ZNdn2fBsTazSy4_lFncaZ2F0n_XLf9zqgFSSo63YlPWgTHIK7zB1vQlSCsaoydA_Fw2KBqor-N8HMhknDeRHDOYNLLyjdTZD3z56P794eaPadg6V533_0c9PuN5--ti2VKr9RAxhAq8WUWn0jMDLFw0sMLUOHa9Ka6L8mcfU38isV2G9cirEzIR75l275Am_icW2pHDUhBqx_S2bSYlWKu9AfH104ntw_EQrTKZNNVUVZSNCjUS2T75KMXHmW7m3HF1M3I2iHERITsxPovokuoHjVRF86QVmv6pKNXxe5agh-jaH02TELAHJLKCEoq786ZCgChbjAYDtltcSaoNxVLlWKQtx51GfjnYkRXB4gZ-pMuFh6lavNQy3ezwDW4azuZSHKxXu3KKog5VKhANpCXhujZpd5A4wO6Ztv1IUq7A7i40U6nLd8tKgxi86QLSw5EFzWNhsZfA8Si6Xk0R7PYMESzOUVFP8aHr12Ouegi3SkSIIhUWXJAyw7G2rAOHiy4W7ANdjGGL3wHTb4ZuuxOj_hQPxXSHskBv5InvbMP98kp5364bdkNPbzlwC6D8DIztLz1AitFI